-- JOHN CHAPTER 13 — The Last Supper: Foot-washing and the Betrayal Foretold
-- 38 verses · Greek text · Word studies · Cross-refs
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════

-- Step 1: Insert chapter metadata
INSERT INTO chapters (book_id, chapter_number, overview, theme, key_word_original, key_word_meaning, outline)
SELECT b.id, 13,
  'John 13 opens the second half of the Gospel — the Book of Glory (chapters 13-21), set entirely in the context of the Passion and its aftermath. The chapter is set at the Last Supper (not the Passover meal in John''s chronology, but the evening before — John places the crucifixion on Nisan 14, the day the Passover lambs were slaughtered). It is the longest single evening in the Gospels, introducing five chapters of intimate teaching to the Twelve (chapters 13-17). The chapter opens with a majestic prologue: ''Jesus knowing that his hour was come that he should depart out of this world unto the Father, having loved his own which were in the world, he loved them unto the end'' (v.1). ''Unto the end'' (eis telos — to the uttermost, completely, finally). The love that sent Jesus into the world now drives him through death out of it. The foot-washing (vv.4-11) is the enacted parable of this love: the Lord and Master removes his garments, girds himself with a towel, and washes his disciples'' feet — the work of the lowest slave. Peter''s horrified protest (v.6) gives Jesus occasion to teach that such washing is necessary for fellowship with him (v.8) and that it is a model for all his disciples (vv.14-17). Jesus then reveals to the disciples that one of them will betray him (vv.18-30). The beloved disciple reclines at Jesus'' bosom; Peter asks him to inquire of Jesus the identity of the betrayer. Jesus identifies Judas by the dipped morsel; ''Satan entered into him'' (v.27); Judas goes out into the night (v.30). The chapter closes with the New Commandment: ''A new commandment I give unto you, That ye love one another; as I have loved you, that ye also love one another'' (v.34), and Peter''s confident claim that he will lay down his life, followed by Jesus'' prediction that Peter will deny him three times before the cock crows (v.38).',
  'Love to the End — Servant Love as the Mark of Discipleship',
  'ἀγαπάω (agapaō)',
  'To love, to cherish, to regard with a self-giving, unconditional love — distinguished from phileō (warm affection) and erōs (romantic love). Agapaō in John 13 is love as action, not feeling: Jesus loved his own ''unto the end'' (v.1) and demonstrated it by washing their feet. The New Commandment (v.34) is to agapaō one another ''as I have loved you'' — the standard of love is the cross-shaped, servant love of Christ himself. The noun agapē and verb agapaō form the backbone of the Upper Room Discourse (chs.13-17). This is not a generalised sentiment but a specific orientation: willing the good of another at cost to oneself.',
  '["Prologue: The Hour of Love (vv.1-3): Before the feast of the passover when Jesus knew that his hour was come that he should depart out of this world unto the Father having loved his own which were in the world he loved them unto the end. And supper being ended the devil having now put into the heart of Judas Iscariot Simon''s son to betray him — Jesus knowing that the Father had given all things into his hands and that he was come from God and went to God","The Foot-washing (vv.4-11): He riseth from supper and laid aside his garments and took a towel and girded himself. After that he poureth water into a bason and began to wash the disciples'' feet and to wipe them with the towel wherewith he was girded. Then cometh he to Simon Peter and Peter saith unto him Lord dost thou wash my feet? Jesus answered and said unto him What I do thou knowest not now but thou shalt know hereafter. Peter saith unto him Thou shalt never wash my feet. Jesus answered him If I wash thee not thou hast no part with me. Simon Peter saith unto him Lord not my feet only but also my hands and my head. Jesus saith to him He that is washed needeth not save to wash his feet but is clean every whit and ye are clean but not all. For he knew who should betray him therefore said he Ye are not all clean","The Example Explained (vv.12-17): So after he had washed their feet and had taken his garments and was set down again he said unto them Know ye what I have done to you? Ye call me Master and Lord and ye say well for so I am. If I then your Lord and Master have washed your feet ye also ought to wash one another''s feet. For I have given you an example that ye should do as I have done to you. Verily verily I say unto you The servant is not greater than his lord neither he that is sent greater than he that sent him. If ye know these things happy are ye if ye do them","The Betrayer Foretold (vv.18-30): I speak not of you all I know whom I have chosen but that the scripture may be fulfilled He that eateth bread with me hath lifted up his heel against me. Now I tell you before it come that when it is come to pass ye may believe that I am he. Verily verily I say unto you He that receiveth whomsoever I send receiveth me and he that receiveth me receiveth him that sent me. When Jesus had thus said he was troubled in spirit and testified and said Verily verily I say unto you that one of you shall betray me. Then the disciples looked one on another doubting of whom he spake. Now there was leaning on Jesus'' bosom one of his disciples whom Jesus loved. Simon Peter therefore beckoned to him that he should ask who it should be of whom he spake. He then lying on Jesus'' breast saith unto him Lord who is it? Jesus answered He it is to whom I shall give a sop when I have dipped it. And when he had dipped the sop he gave it to Judas Iscariot the son of Simon. And after the sop Satan entered into him. Then said Jesus unto him That thou doest do quickly. Now no man at the table knew for what intent he spake this unto him. For some of them thought because Judas had the bag that Jesus had said Buy those things that we have need of against the feast or that he should give something to the poor. He then having received the sop went immediately out and it was night","The New Commandment and Peter''s Denial Foretold (vv.31-38): Therefore when he was gone out Jesus said Now is the Son of man glorified and God is glorified in him. If God be glorified in him God shall also glorify him in himself and shall straightway glorify him. Little children yet a little while I am with you. Ye shall seek me and as I said unto the Jews Whither I go ye cannot come so now I say to you. A new commandment I give unto you That ye love one another as I have loved you that ye also love one another. By this shall all men know that ye are my disciples if ye have love one to another. Simon Peter said unto him Lord whither goest thou? Jesus answered him Whither I go thou canst not follow me now but thou shalt follow me afterwards. Peter said unto him Lord why cannot I follow thee now? I will lay down my life for thy sake. Jesus answered him Wilt thou lay down thy life for my sake? Verily verily I say unto thee The cock shall not crow till thou hast denied me thrice"]'
FROM books b WHERE b.name = 'John';

-- Step 2: Insert all 38 verses
INSERT INTO verses (chapter_id, verse_number, kjv_text, original_text, transliteration, study_note, doctrinal_note)
SELECT c.id, v.verse_number, v.kjv_text, v.original_text, v.transliteration, v.study_note, v.doctrinal_note
FROM chapters c
JOIN books b ON c.book_id = b.id
CROSS JOIN (VALUES
  (1, 'Now before the feast of the passover, when Jesus knew that his hour was come that he should depart out of this world unto the Father, having loved his own which were in the world, he loved them unto the end.',
   'Πρὸ δὲ τῆς ἑορτῆς τοῦ πάσχα εἰδὼς ὁ Ἰησοῦς ὅτι ἦλθεν αὐτοῦ ἡ ὥρα ἵνα μεταβῇ ἐκ τοῦ κόσμου τούτου πρὸς τὸν πατέρα ἀγαπήσας τοὺς ἰδίους τοὺς ἐν τῷ κόσμῳ εἰς τέλος ἠγάπησεν αὐτούς',
   'Pro de tēs heortēs tou pascha eidōs ho Iēsous hoti ēlthen autou hē hōra hina metabē ek tou kosmou toutou pros ton patera agapēsas tous idious tous en tō kosmō eis telos ēgapēsen autous',
   '''Before the feast of the passover'' (pro tēs heortēs tou pascha) — John places this supper the evening before the Passover, making the crucifixion occur on Nisan 14 when the lambs were being slaughtered — Jesus as the true Passover Lamb (19:14; 1 Corinthians 5:7). ''Having loved his own'' (agapēsas tous idious — having loved those who were his own; the participle sets the background). ''Unto the end'' (eis telos) — this phrase has a double meaning: (1) to the end, until the last moment; (2) completely, to the uttermost. Both meanings apply. The cross is both the final act and the fullest expression of his love. John opens the Passion narrative not with betrayal or arrest but with love.',
   NULL),
  (2, 'And supper being ended, the devil having now put into the heart of Judas Iscariot, Simon''s son, to betray him;',
   'καὶ δείπνου γινομένου τοῦ διαβόλου ἤδη βεβληκότος εἰς τὴν καρδίαν Ἰούδα Σίμωνος Ἰσκαριώτου ἵνα αὐτὸν παραδοῖ',
   'kai deipnou ginomenou tou diabolou ēdē beblēkotos eis tēn kardian Iouda Simōnos Iskariōtou hina auton paradoi',
   '''The devil having now put into the heart of Judas... to betray him'' (tou diabolou ēdē beblēkotos eis tēn kardian Iouda — the devil having already thrown into the heart of Judas). ''Beblēkotos'' (perfect participle from ballō: to throw, cast) — the devil had already cast the intention into Judas''s heart before the supper began. ''Diabolos'' (devil, from diaballō: to throw across, slander). The betrayal is presented as a satanic instigation, but Judas is not merely a puppet — he acts as one responsible (v.27; Acts 1:18-19). The mystery of human agency and satanic influence is maintained.',
   NULL),
  (3, 'Jesus knowing that the Father had given all things into his hands, and that he was come from God, and went to God;',
   'εἰδὼς ὁ Ἰησοῦς ὅτι πάντα ἔδωκεν αὐτῷ ὁ πατὴρ εἰς τὰς χεῖρας καὶ ὅτι ἀπὸ θεοῦ ἐξῆλθεν καὶ πρὸς τὸν θεὸν ὑπάγει',
   'eidōs ho Iēsous hoti panta edōken autō ho patēr eis tas cheiras kai hoti apo theou exēlthen kai pros ton theon hypagei',
   '''Knowing that the Father had given all things into his hands'' (eidōs hoti panta edōken autō ho patēr eis tas cheiras) — full knowledge, full authority. ''He was come from God, and went to God'' — the eternal arc of the incarnation: pre-existence → incarnation → passion → glorification. It is precisely because Jesus knows all this — his origin, his destination, his authority — that he is free to perform the servant''s act. True greatness can afford to stoop. The one who has everything can give everything.',
   NULL),
  (4, 'He riseth from supper, and laid aside his garments; and took a towel, and girded himself.',
   'ἐγείρεται ἐκ τοῦ δείπνου καὶ τίθησιν τὰ ἱμάτια καὶ λαβὼν λέντιον διέζωσεν ἑαυτόν',
   'egeiretai ek tou deipnou kai tithēsin ta himatia kai labōn lention diezōsen heauton',
   '''He riseth from supper'' (egeiretai — present tense: rises; vivid, dramatic). ''Laid aside his garments'' (tithēsin ta himatia — lays aside his garments; the same verb used in 10:11,17,18 for ''laying down'' his life). The connection is intentional: laying aside his garments is a parable of laying down his life. He takes a linen towel (lention — a Latin loanword: linteum, a servant''s cloth) and wraps himself with it (diezōsen — girded himself). A slave''s apron. The Lord of glory dresses as a household servant.',
   NULL),
  (5, 'After that he poureth water into a bason, and began to wash the disciples'' feet, and to wipe them with the towel wherewith he was girded.',
   'εἶτα βάλλει ὕδωρ εἰς τὸν νιπτῆρα καὶ ἤρξατο νίπτειν τοὺς πόδας τῶν μαθητῶν καὶ ἐκμάσσειν τῷ λεντίῳ ᾧ ἦν διεζωσμένος',
   'eita ballei hydōr eis ton niptēra kai ērxato niptein tous podas tōn mathētōn kai ekmassein tō lentiō hō ēn diezōsmenos',
   '''Poureth water into a bason'' (ballei hydōr eis ton niptēra — pours water into the basin; niptēr = washing basin, from niptō: to wash). The roads of first-century Palestine were dusty and unpaved; guests removed sandals at the door, and foot-washing was performed by the lowest household slave or by a devoted wife. Jewish law explicitly stated that disciples should not wash their master''s feet. Jesus inverts the entire hierarchy of honour. This act was so shocking that a Rabbinic text (Mekhilta on Exodus) states that a disciple should do everything for his teacher that a slave does, except remove his sandals.',
   NULL),
  (6, 'Then cometh he to Simon Peter: and Peter saith unto him, Lord, dost thou wash my feet?',
   'ἔρχεται οὖν πρὸς Σίμωνα Πέτρον λέγει αὐτῷ Κύριε σύ μου νίπτεις τοὺς πόδας',
   'erchetai oun pros Simōna Petron legei autō Kyrie sy mou nipteis tous podas',
   '''Lord, dost thou wash my feet?'' (Kyrie, sy mou nipteis tous podas?) — the Greek word order is emphatic: ''Lord — YOU — of me — wash — the feet?'' The astonishment is in the reversal: the Lord performing the slave''s task. Peter''s protest is entirely comprehensible and, within the normal framework of honour, entirely appropriate. The scandal of the cross has the same shape: that the holy One should take the place of the guilty is equally incomprehensible to natural reason.',
   NULL),
  (7, 'Jesus answered and said unto him, What I do thou knowest not now; but thou shalt know hereafter.',
   'ἀπεκρίθη Ἰησοῦς καὶ εἶπεν αὐτῷ Ὃ ἐγὼ ποιῶ σὺ οὐκ οἶδας ἄρτι γνώσῃ δὲ μετὰ ταῦτα',
   'apekrithē Iēsous kai eipen autō Ho egō poiō sy ouk oidas arti gnōsē de meta tauta',
   '''Thou knowest not now; but thou shalt know hereafter'' (ouk oidas arti, gnōsē de meta tauta — you do not know now, but you will know after these things). Understanding comes after the event — after the cross, resurrection, and Pentecost. This is the pattern of discipleship in John: events are lived before they are understood; the Spirit then ''brings to remembrance'' (14:26). Faith walks ahead of full comprehension.',
   NULL),
  (8, 'Peter saith unto him, Thou shalt never wash my feet. Jesus answered him, If I wash thee not, thou hast no part with me.',
   'λέγει αὐτῷ Πέτρος Οὐ μὴ νίψῃς μου τοὺς πόδας εἰς τὸν αἰῶνα ἀπεκρίθη Ἰησοῦς αὐτῷ Ἐὰν μὴ νίψω σε οὐκ ἔχεις μέρος μετ᾽ ἐμοῦ',
   'legei autō Petros Ou mē nipsēs mou tous podas eis ton aiōna apekrithē Iēsous autō Ean mē nipsō se ouk echeis meros met emou',
   '''Thou shalt never wash my feet'' (ou mē nipsēs mou tous podas eis ton aiōna — you shall certainly not wash my feet into the age). ''Ou mē'' with the subjunctive is the strongest negation in Greek: absolutely not, under no circumstances. Peter''s refusal is vigorous and loyal-sounding but misses the point. ''If I wash thee not, thou hast no part with me'' (ean mē nipsō se, ouk echeis meros met emou — if I do not wash you, you have no share with me). The foot-washing represents cleansing that only Jesus can give; to refuse it is to forfeit fellowship. The application extends to the whole redemptive work: one cannot have ''part'' with Christ while refusing his atoning service.',
   NULL),
  (9, 'Simon Peter saith unto him, Lord, not my feet only, but also my hands and my head.',
   'λέγει αὐτῷ Σίμων Πέτρος Κύριε μὴ τοὺς πόδας μου μόνον ἀλλὰ καὶ τὰς χεῖρας καὶ τὴν κεφαλήν',
   'legei autō Simōn Petros Kyrie mē tous podas mou monon alla kai tas cheiras kai tēn kephalēn',
   'Peter swings from absolute refusal to lavish demand — typical of his impulsive character. ''Not my feet only, but also my hands and my head'' — an all-or-nothing response once he grasps the stakes. The irony is charming: Peter is so eager for complete fellowship that he wants to be washed from head to foot. Jesus'' response distinguishes between bathing (the once-for-all washing of regeneration) and foot-washing (ongoing cleansing of daily defilement).',
   NULL),
  (10, 'Jesus saith to him, He that is washed needeth not save to wash his feet, but is clean every whit: and ye are clean, but not all.',
   'λέγει αὐτῷ ὁ Ἰησοῦς Ὁ λελουμένος οὐχὶ χρείαν ἔχει εἰ μὴ τοὺς πόδας νίψασθαι ἀλλ᾽ ἔστιν καθαρὸς ὅλος καὶ ὑμεῖς καθαροί ἐστε ἀλλ᾽ οὐχὶ πάντες',
   'legei autō ho Iēsous Ho leloumenos ouchi chreian echei ei mē tous podas nipsasthai all estin katharos holos kai hymeis katharoi este all ouchi pantes',
   '''He that is washed'' (ho leloumenos — the one who has bathed; perfect participle from louō: to bathe the whole body) ''needeth not save to wash his feet'' (nipsasthai — niptō: to wash a part of the body). The distinction is between full bathing (regeneration, once-for-all) and foot-washing (ongoing cleansing from daily defilement, 1 John 1:9). ''Ye are clean'' (katharoi este — clean, pure) ''but not all'' — a reference to Judas. The word ''clean'' (katharos) will reappear in 15:3: ''Ye are clean through the word which I have spoken unto you.''',
   NULL),
  (11, 'For he knew who should betray him; therefore said he, Ye are not all clean.',
   'ᾔδει γὰρ τὸν παραδιδόντα αὐτόν διὰ τοῦτο εἶπεν Οὐχὶ πάντες καθαροί ἐστε',
   'ēdei gar ton paradidonta auton dia touto eipen Ouchi pantes katharoi este',
   'John provides the editorial explanation: the exception in ''not all clean'' refers to Judas (ton paradidonta auton — the one betraying him; present participle: the one in the process of betraying). Judas had participated in the foot-washing — Jesus had washed his feet too — but the physical washing could not cleanse the one who had not received the inward reality. External religious participation does not guarantee inward renewal.',
   NULL),
  (12, 'So after he had washed their feet, and had taken his garments, and was set down again, he said unto them, Know ye what I have done to you?',
   'ὅτε οὖν ἔνιψεν τοὺς πόδας αὐτῶν καὶ ἔλαβεν τὰ ἱμάτια αὐτοῦ ἀναπεσὼν πάλιν εἶπεν αὐτοῖς Γινώσκετε τί πεποίηκα ὑμῖν',
   'hote oun enipsen tous podas autōn kai elaben ta himatia autou anapesōn palin eipen autois Ginōskete ti pepoiēka hymin',
   '''Taken his garments'' (elaben ta himatia — took back his garments; the same verb as ''laid aside'' in v.4 in reverse). The enacted parable is complete; now comes the explanation. ''Know ye what I have done to you?'' (Ginōskete ti pepoiēka hymin? — do you understand what I have done to you?) The question is rhetorical — they know the action but not the full meaning. Jesus is about to unfold it.',
   NULL),
  (13, 'Ye call me Master and Lord: and ye say well; for so I am.',
   'ὑμεῖς φωνεῖτέ με ὁ διδάσκαλος καὶ ὁ κύριος καὶ καλῶς λέγετε εἰμὶ γάρ',
   'hymeis phōneite me ho didaskalos kai ho kyrios kai kalōs legete eimi gar',
   '''Ye call me Master and Lord'' (ho didaskalos kai ho kyrios — the Teacher and the Lord). Both titles are used with the definite article, indicating they are official, recognised titles. ''And ye say well'' (kalōs legete — you say rightly) ''for so I am'' (eimi gar — for I am). Jesus affirms the titles — he does not deflect the honour. The foot-washing is not a denial of his lordship but an expression of it: the Lord''s lordship is servant-shaped. True authority serves; it does not merely command.',
   NULL),
  (14, 'If I then, your Lord and Master, have washed your feet; ye also ought to wash one another''s feet.',
   'εἰ οὖν ἐγὼ ἔνιψα ὑμῶν τοὺς πόδας ὁ κύριος καὶ ὁ διδάσκαλος καὶ ὑμεῖς ὀφείλετε ἀλλήλων νίπτειν τοὺς πόδας',
   'ei oun egō enipsa hymōn tous podas ho kyrios kai ho didaskalos kai hymeis opheilete allēlōn niptein tous podas',
   '''Ye also ought to wash one another''s feet'' (kai hymeis opheilete allēlōn niptein tous podas — you also are obligated to wash one another''s feet; opheilō = to owe a debt, be obligated). The argument moves from example to obligation: if the greater serves the lesser, the lesser must serve one another. Some traditions (Mennonites, some Catholic and Anglican orders) practice literal foot-washing as a sacramental rite; the broader application is mutual humble service in the community of faith.',
   NULL),
  (15, 'For I have given you an example, that ye should do as I have done to you.',
   'ὑπόδειγμα γὰρ ἔδωκα ὑμῖν ἵνα καθὼς ἐγὼ ἐποίησα ὑμῖν καὶ ὑμεῖς ποιῆτε',
   'hypodeigma gar edōka hymin hina kathōs egō epoiēsa hymin kai hymeis poiēte',
   '''An example'' (hypodeigma — an example, a pattern set for imitation; from hypo: under + deiknymi: to show). The same word is used in James 5:10 (''example of suffering'') and Hebrews 4:11 (''example of unbelief''). ''As I have done to you'' (kathōs egō epoiēsa — just as I did) — the standard is not ''be helpful'' or ''be nice'' but ''exactly as I, the Lord, served you.'' The measure is the cross-shaped service of the Son of God.',
   NULL),
  (16, 'Verily, verily, I say unto you, The servant is not greater than his lord; neither he that is sent greater than he that sent him.',
   'ἀμὴν ἀμὴν λέγω ὑμῖν οὐκ ἔστιν δοῦλος μείζων τοῦ κυρίου αὐτοῦ οὐδὲ ἀπόστολος μείζων τοῦ πέμψαντος αὐτόν',
   'amēn amēn legō hymin ouk estin doulos meizōn tou kyriou autou oude apostolos meizōn tou pempsantos auton',
   '''The servant is not greater than his lord'' (ouk estin doulos meizōn tou kyriou autou). This proverb appears also in Matthew 10:24 and John 15:20. Here the application is to humility in service: if the Lord served, the servant must serve. ''Neither he that is sent greater than he that sent him'' (oude apostolos meizōn tou pempsantos auton — nor an apostle greater than the one who sent him). ''Apostolos'' literally means ''one sent'' — its only use in John. The apostle derives authority from the Sender; the Sender is the Lord who washed feet.',
   NULL),
  (17, 'If ye know these things, happy are ye if ye do them.',
   'εἰ ταῦτα οἴδατε μακάριοί ἐστε ἐὰν ποιῆτε αὐτά',
   'ei tauta oidate makarioi este ean poiēte auta',
   '''Happy are ye if ye do them'' (makarioi este ean poiēte auta — blessed are you if you do them). ''Makarios'' (blessed, happy) — the same word used in the Beatitudes (Matthew 5:3-12). Knowledge without action produces guilt rather than blessing. The blessing is in the doing (James 1:25). John''s Gospel, often regarded as purely contemplative, here insists that understanding must be lived out. Orthodoxy without orthopraxy is incomplete.',
   NULL),
  (18, 'I speak not of you all: I know whom I have chosen: but that the scripture may be fulfilled, He that eateth bread with me hath lifted up his heel against me.',
   'οὐ περὶ πάντων ὑμῶν λέγω ἐγὼ οἶδα τίνας ἐξελεξάμην ἀλλ᾽ ἵνα ἡ γραφὴ πληρωθῇ Ὁ τρώγων μου τὸν ἄρτον ἐπῆρεν ἐπ᾽ ἐμὲ τὴν πτέρναν αὐτοῦ',
   'ou peri pantōn hymōn legō egō oida tinas exelexamēn all hina hē graphē plērōthē Ho trōgōn mou ton arton epēren ep eme tēn pternan autou',
   '''I know whom I have chosen'' (oida tinas exelexamēn — I know the ones I selected; aorist: the selection is complete). The election of the Twelve includes Judas — not accidentally but purposefully, ''that the scripture may be fulfilled.'' Quoting Psalm 41:9: ''He that eateth bread with me hath lifted up his heel against me.'' ''Lifted up his heel'' (epēren tēn pternan — raised his heel) — a metaphor of betrayal; a trusted companion turns and kicks. David wrote of Ahithophel; the Holy Spirit intended Jesus and Judas. The betrayal is not a divine accident but a divinely anticipated and overruled event.',
   NULL),
  (19, 'Now I tell you before it come, that, when it is come to pass, ye may believe that I am he.',
   'ἀπ᾽ ἄρτι λέγω ὑμῖν πρὸ τοῦ γενέσθαι ἵνα πιστεύσητε ὅταν γένηται ὅτι ἐγώ εἰμι',
   'ap arti legō hymin pro tou genesthai hina pisteusēte hotan genētai hoti egō eimi',
   '''That when it is come to pass, ye may believe that I am he'' (hoti egō eimi — that I AM). The foreknowledge and forewarning of the betrayal is itself a proof of divine identity. ''Egō eimi'' (I AM) echoes the divine name (Exodus 3:14; Isaiah 43:10). Jesus predicts in order to strengthen faith when the prediction is fulfilled. The disciples will remember his words (16:4) and the fulfilment will confirm rather than destroy their faith.',
   NULL),
  (20, 'Verily, verily, I say unto you, He that receiveth whomsoever I send receiveth me; and he that receiveth me receiveth him that sent me.',
   'ἀμὴν ἀμὴν λέγω ὑμῖν ὁ λαμβάνων ἄν τινα πέμψω ἐμὲ λαμβάνει ὁ δὲ ἐμὲ λαμβάνων λαμβάνει τὸν πέμψαντά με',
   'amēn amēn legō hymin ho lambanōn an tina pempsō eme lambanei ho de eme lambanōn lambanei ton pempsanta me',
   'This principle of agency (the envoy carries the authority of the sender) is inserted here perhaps as a counterweight to the news of betrayal: despite Judas''s failure, the mission of the Twelve continues. Those sent in Jesus'' name carry his authority; receiving them is receiving Christ, and receiving Christ is receiving the Father. The chain of representation extends from the Father through the Son through the apostles to all who receive the message.',
   NULL),
  (21, 'When Jesus had thus said, he was troubled in spirit, and testified, and said, Verily, verily, I say unto you, that one of you shall betray me.',
   'Ταῦτα εἰπὼν ὁ Ἰησοῦς ἐταράχθη τῷ πνεύματι καὶ ἐμαρτύρησεν καὶ εἶπεν Ἀμὴν ἀμὴν λέγω ὑμῖν ὅτι εἷς ἐξ ὑμῶν παραδώσει με',
   'Tauta eipōn ho Iēsous etarachthē tō pneumati kai emartyrésen kai eipen Amēn amēn legō hymin hoti heis ex hymōn paradōsei me',
   '''He was troubled in spirit'' (etarachthē tō pneumati — was agitated/shaken in the spirit; the same verb as 11:33, where he was ''troubled'' at Lazarus''s tomb, and 12:27, where his soul was ''troubled''). Jesus is not unmoved by the betrayal. ''Testified'' (emartyrésen — bore witness, made a solemn declaration). The announcement ''one of you shall betray me'' is a formal testimony, a solemn statement of terrible truth. The use of ''Verily, verily'' marks it as a pronouncement of the highest gravity.',
   NULL),
  (22, 'Then the disciples looked one on another, doubting of whom he spake.',
   'ἔβλεπον οὖν εἰς ἀλλήλους οἱ μαθηταί ἀπορούμενοι περὶ τίνος λέγει',
   'eblepon oun eis allēlous hoi mathētai aporoumenoi peri tinos legei',
   '''Doubting of whom he spake'' (aporoumenoi peri tinos legei — perplexed, at a loss as to whom he was speaking). ''Aporoumenoi'' (from aporeo: to be at a loss, without a way through; a + poros: no passage). The disciples are genuinely baffled — they cannot identify the traitor by reading his face or manner. Judas had concealed his treachery perfectly. Their exchanged glances reveal innocent incomprehension. (The Synoptics record each asking, ''Is it I?'' — Matthew 26:22; Mark 14:19.)',
   NULL),
  (23, 'Now there was leaning on Jesus'' bosom one of his disciples, whom Jesus loved.',
   'ἦν δὲ ἀνακείμενος εἷς ἐκ τῶν μαθητῶν αὐτοῦ ἐν τῷ κόλπῳ τοῦ Ἰησοῦ ὃν ἠγάπα ὁ Ἰησοῦς',
   'ēn de anakeimenos heis ek tōn mathētōn autou en tō kolpō tou Iēsou hon ēgapa ho Iēsous',
   '''Leaning on Jesus'' bosom'' (anakeimenos en tō kolpō tou Iēsou — reclining in the bosom of Jesus). At ancient banquets, diners reclined on their left side on couches arranged in a U-shape, leaning on the left elbow; the person to one''s right would have their head at one''s breast level. ''The disciple whom Jesus loved'' (hon ēgapa ho Iēsous — whom Jesus kept loving; imperfect: ongoing, habitual love) — the Beloved Disciple, the author of this Gospel, traditionally identified as John son of Zebedee. He is introduced here for the first time in this role. The phrase ''in the bosom'' (en tō kolpō) echoes 1:18: ''the only begotten Son, which is in the bosom of the Father'' — the Beloved Disciple''s intimacy with Jesus mirrors Jesus'' intimacy with the Father.',
   NULL),
  (24, 'Simon Peter therefore beckoned to him, that he should ask who it should be of whom he spake.',
   'νεύει οὖν τούτῳ Σίμων Πέτρος πυθέσθαι τίς ἂν εἴη περὶ οὗ λέγει',
   'neuei oun toutō Simōn Petros pythesthai tis an eiē peri hou legei',
   '''Beckoned'' (neuei — nodded, gestured; from neuō: to nod). Peter signals across the table to the Beloved Disciple to ask on his behalf. This detail reflects the seating: the Beloved Disciple is next to Jesus (at his right), Peter is further away. Peter''s action shows his characteristic directness: he wants to know who the traitor is. The inquiry proceeds through the one closest to Jesus — a pattern: access to truth comes through proximity to Christ.',
   NULL),
  (25, 'He then lying on Jesus'' breast saith unto him, Lord, who is it?',
   'ἀναπεσὼν δὲ ἐκεῖνος οὕτως ἐπὶ τὸ στῆθος τοῦ Ἰησοῦ λέγει αὐτῷ Κύριε τίς ἐστιν',
   'anapesōn de ekeinos houtōs epi to stēthos tou Iēsou legei autō Kyrie tis estin',
   '''Lying on Jesus'' breast'' (anapesōn epi to stēthos tou Iēsou — having leaned back upon the chest of Jesus). The physical intimacy is striking. ''Lord, who is it?'' (Kyrie, tis estin?) — a simple, urgent question. The question is asked privately (or at least quietly); the answer is given privately. The rest of the disciples do not hear or understand (v.28).',
   NULL),
  (26, 'Jesus answered, He it is, to whom I shall give a sop, when I have dipped it. And when he had dipped the sop, he gave it to Judas Iscariot, the son of Simon.',
   'ἀποκρίνεται ὁ Ἰησοῦς Ἐκεῖνός ἐστιν ᾧ ἐγὼ βάψω τὸ ψωμίον καὶ δώσω αὐτῷ βάψας οὖν τὸ ψωμίον λαμβάνει καὶ δίδωσιν Ἰούδᾳ Σίμωνος Ἰσκαριώτῃ',
   'apokrinetai ho Iēsous Ekeinos estin hō egō bapsō to psōmion kai dōsō autō bapsas oun to psōmion lambanei kai didōsin Iouda Simōnos Iskariōtē',
   '''A sop'' (to psōmion — a morsel of bread, a small piece; diminutive of psōmos). The host at a banquet would dip a piece of bread in sauce and hand it to a guest as a mark of special honour. Jesus gives the sop to Judas — an act of extraordinary, final grace. Even in the moment of identification, the gesture is one of hospitality and honour. This is love to ''the uttermost'' — love extended to the betrayer himself. Judas receives the sop and with it, his final opportunity.',
   NULL),
  (27, 'And after the sop Satan entered into him. Then said Jesus unto him, That thou doest, do quickly.',
   'καὶ μετὰ τὸ ψωμίον τότε εἰσῆλθεν εἰς ἐκεῖνον ὁ Σατανᾶς λέγει οὖν αὐτῷ ὁ Ἰησοῦς Ὃ ποιεῖς ποίησον τάχιον',
   'kai meta to psōmion tote eisēlthen eis ekeinon ho Satanas legei oun autō ho Iēsous Ho poieis poiēson tachion',
   '''After the sop Satan entered into him'' (meta to psōmion tote eisēlthen eis ekeinon ho Satanas) — the final, full Satanic possession occurs at this moment. The sop received without repentance marks the point of no return for Judas. Grace refused becomes the occasion of hardening. ''That thou doest, do quickly'' (Ho poieis, poiēson tachion — what you are doing, do it more quickly). Jesus commands the betrayal — not as approval but as sovereign authority. He is not a victim carried away by events but the master who permits and times his own arrest. Even the betrayal is under his control.',
   NULL),
  (28, 'Now no man at the table knew for what intent he spake this unto him.',
   'τοῦτο δὲ οὐδεὶς ἔγνω τῶν ἀνακειμένων πρὸς τί εἶπεν αὐτῷ',
   'touto de oudeis egnō tōn anakeimenōn pros ti eipen autō',
   'The exchange between Jesus and Judas is not understood by the other disciples. Even the Beloved Disciple (who knew the sign) apparently does not communicate this to the others, or the significance is not grasped. The darkness that is Judas''s spiritual state is also an epistemic darkness: no one sees what is happening. The moment of history''s greatest treachery is invisible to those present.',
   NULL),
  (29, 'For some of them thought, because Judas had the bag, that Jesus had said unto him, Buy those things that we have need of against the feast; or, that he should give something to the poor.',
   'τινὲς γὰρ ἐδόκουν ἐπεὶ τὸ γλωσσόκομον εἶχεν Ἰούδας ὅτι λέγει αὐτῷ ὁ Ἰησοῦς Ἀγόρασον ὧν χρείαν ἔχομεν εἰς τὴν ἑορτήν ἢ τοῖς πτωχοῖς ἵνα τι δῷ',
   'tines gar edokoun epei to glōssokomon eichen Ioudas hoti legei autō ho Iēsous Agorazon hōn chreian echomen eis tēn heortēn ē tois ptōchois hina ti dō',
   'The disciples rationalise the departure of Judas in the most innocent terms: he is on an errand. ''Buy those things'' or ''give to the poor'' — the very justifications Judas himself had used in 12:5 (''give to the poor'') now echo ironically. The trusted treasurer is trusted to the last — even by those who should suspect. Evil often works under the cover of the plausible.',
   NULL),
  (30, 'He then having received the sop went immediately out: and it was night.',
   'λαβὼν οὖν τὸ ψωμίον ἐκεῖνος ἐξῆλθεν εὐθύς ἦν δὲ νύξ',
   'labōn oun to psōmion ekeinos exēlthen euthys ēn de nyx',
   '''He then having received the sop went immediately out'' (exēlthen euthys — went out immediately; immediately without hesitation). ''And it was night'' (ēn de nyx) — three words in Greek, one of the most evocative in the entire Gospel. Night is the realm of Judas, of the prince of this world, of those who will not come to the light (3:19-20). In John''s symbolic world, ''night'' is not merely a time of day but a spiritual state. Judas steps out of the light of Christ''s presence into the darkness he has chosen.',
   NULL),
  (31, 'Therefore, when he was gone out, Jesus said, Now is the Son of man glorified, and God is glorified in him.',
   'ὅτε οὖν ἐξῆλθεν λέγει Ἰησοῦς Νῦν ἐδοξάσθη ὁ υἱὸς τοῦ ἀνθρώπου καὶ ὁ θεὸς ἐδοξάσθη ἐν αὐτῷ',
   'hote oun exēlthen legei Iēsous Nyn edoxasthē ho huios tou anthrōpou kai ho theos edoxasthē en autō',
   '''Now is the Son of man glorified'' (nyn edoxasthē — now has been glorified; aorist, speaking of the future passion as already accomplished from the divine perspective). The departure of Judas into the night triggers Jesus'' farewell discourse. With the betrayer gone, he speaks freely to the Eleven. ''God is glorified in him'' — the mutual glorification of Father and Son through the Passion is the culmination of the Gospel''s theme. Glory is not in triumph over enemies but in obedient self-giving love.',
   NULL),
  (32, 'If God be glorified in him, God shall also glorify him in himself, and shall straightway glorify him.',
   'εἰ ὁ θεὸς ἐδοξάσθη ἐν αὐτῷ καὶ ὁ θεὸς δοξάσει αὐτὸν ἐν αὐτῷ καὶ εὐθὺς δοξάσει αὐτόν',
   'ei ho theos edoxasthē en autō kai ho theos doxasei auton en autō kai euthys doxasei auton',
   '''God shall also glorify him in himself'' (ho theos doxasei auton en autō — God will glorify him in himself; the Father glorifies the Son by the resurrection, ascension, and Pentecost). ''Straightway'' (euthys — immediately, without delay). The Father''s glorification of the Son follows immediately upon the Son''s glorification of the Father through the cross. There is no long delay between crucifixion and resurrection — three days is ''straightway'' in God''s economy.',
   NULL),
  (33, 'Little children, yet a little while I am with you. Ye shall seek me: and as I said unto the Jews, Whither I go, ye cannot come; so now I say to you.',
   'τεκνία ἔτι μικρὸν μεθ᾽ ὑμῶν εἰμι ζητήσετέ με καὶ καθὼς εἶπον τοῖς Ἰουδαίοις ὅτι ὅπου ἐγὼ ὑπάγω ὑμεῖς οὐ δύνασθε ἐλθεῖν καὶ ὑμῖν λέγω ἄρτι',
   'teknia eti mikron meth hymōn eimi zētēsete me kai kathōs eipon tois Ioudaiois hoti hopou egō hypagō hymeis ou dynasthe elthein kai hymin legō arti',
   '''Little children'' (teknia — dear little children; a tender diminutive; in John only here; in 1 John seven times). This is the only time in the Fourth Gospel that Jesus uses this term of address to the disciples — it marks a new intimacy now that Judas is gone. ''Yet a little while I am with you'' — the Passion is imminent; hours remain. ''Ye cannot come'' — temporarily, not permanently; for now they cannot follow him through death, but they will (13:36; 14:3; 17:24).',
   NULL),
  (34, 'A new commandment I give unto you, That ye love one another; as I have loved you, that ye also love one another.',
   'ἐντολὴν καινὴν δίδωμι ὑμῖν ἵνα ἀγαπᾶτε ἀλλήλους καθὼς ἠγάπησα ὑμᾶς ἵνα καὶ ὑμεῖς ἀγαπᾶτε ἀλλήλους',
   'entolēn kainēn didōmi hymin hina agapate allēlous kathōs ēgapēsa hymas hina kai hymeis agapate allēlous',
   '''A new commandment'' (entolēn kainēn — a new commandment; kainēn: new in quality, not merely in time; kainos vs. neos). The command to love is not new in itself — Leviticus 19:18 commands love of neighbour. The newness is in the standard: ''as I have loved you'' (kathōs ēgapēsa hymas — just as I loved you; the love of the cross is the measure). No previous standard had been set this high. And the scope: ''one another'' — the covenant community, those united in Christ. This love is distinctively Christian: cross-shaped, self-giving, sacrificial.',
   NULL),
  (35, 'By this shall all men know that ye are my disciples, if ye have love one to another.',
   'ἐν τούτῳ γνώσονται πάντες ὅτι ἐμοὶ μαθηταί ἐστε ἐὰν ἀγάπην ἔχητε ἐν ἀλλήλοις',
   'en toutō gnōsontai pantes hoti emoi mathētai este ean agapēn echēte en allēlois',
   '''By this shall all men know'' (en toutō gnōsontai pantes — by this all people will know). The distinguishing mark of discipleship, the badge of Christianity, is not orthodoxy of belief alone, not correct ritual, not ecclesiastical belonging, but agapē love in the community. Tertullian (c.200 AD) reports pagans observing: ''See how they love one another!'' This was the great witness of the early church — a community of mutual love crossing ethnic, social, and economic barriers in the Roman world.',
   NULL),
  (36, 'Simon Peter said unto him, Lord, whither goest thou? Jesus answered him, Whither I go, thou canst not follow me now; but thou shalt follow me afterwards.',
   'Λέγει αὐτῷ Σίμων Πέτρος Κύριε ποῦ ὑπάγεις ἀπεκρίθη αὐτῷ Ἰησοῦς Ὅπου ὑπάγω οὐ δύνασαί μοι νῦν ἀκολουθῆσαι ἀκολουθήσεις δὲ ὕστερον',
   'Legei autō Simōn Petros Kyrie pou hypageis apekrithē autō Iēsous Hopou hypagō ou dynasai moi nyn akolouthēsai akolouthēseis de hysteron',
   '''Lord, whither goest thou?'' Peter, characteristically, focuses on the departure rather than the love commandment. He cannot bear the thought of Jesus leaving. ''Thou canst not follow me now'' (ou dynasai moi nyn akolouthēsai — you are not able to follow me now). The ''now'' is important: the prohibition is temporary. ''Thou shalt follow me afterwards'' (akolouthēseis de hysteron — you will follow later). Jesus is speaking of his death; Peter will follow him in martyrdom — traditionally crucifixion, upside-down (21:18-19). Peter''s road to the cross runs through denial and restoration first.',
   NULL),
  (37, 'Peter said unto him, Lord, why cannot I follow thee now? I will lay down my life for thy sake.',
   'λέγει αὐτῷ ὁ Πέτρος Κύριε διὰ τί οὐ δύναμαί σοι ἀκολουθῆσαι ἄρτι τὴν ψυχήν μου ὑπὲρ σοῦ θήσω',
   'legei autō ho Petros Kyrie dia ti ou dynamai soi akolouthēsai arti tēn psychēn mou hyper sou thēsō',
   '''I will lay down my life for thy sake'' (tēn psychēn mou hyper sou thēsō — I will lay down my soul/life on your behalf). Peter uses the exact language Jesus has used in 10:11,17,18 for the Good Shepherd laying down his life. He means it sincerely — Peter is genuinely courageous (he will draw his sword in Gethsemane, 18:10). But his courage is natural courage, unaided by grace; it will fail. The self-confidence is real; the self-knowledge is absent. True courage in discipleship is the gift of the Spirit, not the achievement of the will (Acts 4:13).',
   NULL),
  (38, 'Jesus answered him, Wilt thou lay down thy life for my sake? Verily, verily, I say unto thee, The cock shall not crow, till thou hast denied me thrice.',
   'ἀπεκρίθη αὐτῷ ὁ Ἰησοῦς Τὴν ψυχήν σου ὑπὲρ ἐμοῦ θήσεις ἀμὴν ἀμὴν λέγω σοι οὐ μὴ ἀλέκτωρ φωνήσῃ ἕως οὗ ἀρνήσῃ με τρίς',
   'apekrithē autō ho Iēsous Tēn psychēn sou hyper emou thēseis amēn amēn legō soi ou mē alektōr phōnēsē heōs hou arnēsē me tris',
   '''Wilt thou lay down thy life for my sake?'' The question is not a rebuke but a gentle, knowing challenge. Jesus accepts the intention and predicts the failure. ''The cock shall not crow, till thou hast denied me thrice'' (ou mē alektōr phōnēsē heōs hou arnēsē me tris) — ''alektōr'' (cockerel; the crowing between midnight and 3am, or at dawn). ''Arnēsē'' (you will deny; from arneomai — to disown, disavow). The prediction is precise: three denials, one crowing, one night. It will be fulfilled exactly in 18:15-27. But Jesus'' foreknowledge of the failure does not mean he has abandoned Peter — 21:15-19 shows the restoration.',
   NULL)
) AS v(verse_number, kjv_text, original_text, transliteration, study_note, doctrinal_note)
WHERE b.name = 'John' AND c.chapter_number = 13;
